{"displayTopicName":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","topicTokens":[{"text":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","type":"text"}],"paragraphsBySubtopic":{"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh":[{"text":"Perek Ha’ish mekadesh begins with the first Mishnah of the second perek:\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"type":"bold","tokens":[{"text":"האיש","type":"text"}]},{"text":" מקדש בו ובשלוחו\nהאשה מתקדשת בה ובשלוחה\nהאיש מקדש את בתו כשהיא נערה בו ובשלוחו:","type":"text"}],"direction":"rtl"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":null,"rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Words","type":"local","tokens":[{"text":"Words","type":"text"}],"targetSubtopic":"Words","targetTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Literal","type":"local","tokens":[{"text":"Literal","type":"text"}],"targetSubtopic":"Literal","targetTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Basic","type":"local","tokens":[{"text":"Basic","type":"text"}],"targetSubtopic":"Basic","targetTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Analysis","type":"local","tokens":[{"text":"Analysis","type":"text"}],"targetSubtopic":"Analysis","targetTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Commentary","type":"local","tokens":[{"text":"Commentary","type":"text"}],"targetSubtopic":"Commentary","targetTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Summary","type":"local","tokens":[{"text":"Summary","type":"text"}],"targetSubtopic":"Summary","targetTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh"}]}]}],"Words":[{"text":"These are the possible meanings of the words in the Mishnah, without considering context.","type":"text"},{"type":"tool_tip","tokens":[{"text":"Use this step to get better at guessing which meaning a given word has in the current context.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"האיש","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"האיש","type":"text"}],"pathString":"האיש","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"מקדש","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"מקדש","type":"text"}],"pathString":"מקדש","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"בו","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"בו","type":"text"}],"pathString":"בו","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"ובשלוחו","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"ובשלוחו","type":"text"}],"pathString":"ובשלוחו","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":"\n","type":"text"},{"text":"האשה","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"האשה","type":"text"}],"pathString":"האשה","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"מתקדשת","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"מתקדשת","type":"text"}],"pathString":"מתקדשת","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"בה","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"בה","type":"text"}],"pathString":"בה","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"ובשלוחה","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"ובשלוחה","type":"text"}],"pathString":"ובשלוחה","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":"\n","type":"text"},{"text":"האיש","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"האיש","type":"text"}],"pathString":"האיש","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"מקדש","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"מקדש","type":"text"}],"pathString":"מקדש","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"את","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"את","type":"text"}],"pathString":"את","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"בתו","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"בתו","type":"text"}],"pathString":"בתו","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"כשהיא","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"כשהיא","type":"text"}],"pathString":"כשהיא","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"נערה","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"נערה","type":"text"}],"pathString":"נערה","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"בו","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"בו","type":"text"}],"pathString":"בו","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"ובשלוחו","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"ובשלוחו","type":"text"}],"pathString":"ובשלוחו","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"},{"text":":","type":"text"}],"direction":"rtl"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":"right","rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Literal","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Literal","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Literal","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Words"}]}]}],"Literal":[{"text":"This is a literal translation of the Mishnah, identifying the general meanings of the words but not adapting them to fit the current context.","type":"text"},{"type":"tool_tip","tokens":[{"text":"You can use this step to practice going from the literal meanings of the words to the contextual meaning of the text.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"\nThe Mishnah begins:\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִישׁ מְקַדֵּשׁ בּוֹ וּבִשְׁלוּחוֹ\n","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"ha’ish mekadesh bo ub’shlucho","type":"text"}]}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“The man is/is being ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"mekadesh","type":"text"}]},{"text":" via himself and/or via his ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"shaliach","type":"text"}]},{"text":" i.e. emissary.”\nThe expression “to be ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"mekadesh","type":"text"}]},{"text":"” can have a range of meanings. Literally it means for someone to make holiness. Practically that could refer to a man who makes ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"kiddush","type":"text"}]},{"text":" before a Shabbos meal, a man who halachically engages a woman for marriage, or anyone who does an action that increases holiness in the world.\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִשָּׁה מִתְקַדֶּשֶׁת בָּהּ וּבִשְׁלוּחָהּ\n","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"ha’isha miskadeshes bah ub’shluchah","type":"text"}]}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“The woman is ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"miskadeshes","type":"text"}]},{"text":" via herself and/or via her ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"shaliach","type":"text"}]},{"text":" i.e. emissary.”\nA woman can “be ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"miskadeshes","type":"text"}]},{"text":"” if she “becomes holy,” i.e. via any of the aforementioned meanings.\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִישׁ מְקַדֵּשׁ אֶת בִּתּוֹ כְּשֶׁהִיא נַעֲרָה בּוֹ וּבִשְׁלוּחוֹ\n","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"ha’ish mekadesh es bito k’sh’hi na’arah bo ub’shlucho","type":"text"}]}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“The man is/is being ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"mekadesh","type":"text"}]},{"text":" his daughter when she is a ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"na’ara","type":"text"}]},{"text":" via himself and/or via her ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"shaliach","type":"text"}]},{"text":" i.e. emissary.”\n","type":"text"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":null,"rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Words","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Words","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Words","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Literal"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Basic","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Basic","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Basic","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Literal"}]}]}],"Basic":[{"text":"This is a “basic” explanation of the Mishnah, clarifying the contextual meanings of the words and answering questions a beginner might have, but not dealing with analytical questions or observations.","type":"text"},{"type":"tool_tip","tokens":[{"text":"Use this step to practice taking the basic meaning of the text and identifying difficulties or observations that will be addressed by the later commentators.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִישׁ מְקַדֵּשׁ בּוֹ וּבִשְׁלוּחוֹ","type":"text"}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“The man is/is being ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"mekadesh","type":"text"}]},{"text":" via himself and/or via his ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"shaliach","type":"text"}]},{"text":" i.e. emissary.”\nGiven that we are in meseches Kiddushin which deals primarily with marriage law, we can determine that the meaning of מקדש here is the creation of the ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"kiddushin","type":"text"}]},{"text":" initial stage of marriage that precedes the final ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"nisuyin","type":"text"}]},{"text":" stage. Once a man is ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"mekadesh","type":"text"}]},{"text":" a woman, she would need a get i.e. bill of divorce from him in order to remarry.\nAdditionally, “ongoing” verbs in the Mishnah generally signify the permissibly of an action. So, “the man is being mekadesh” really means \"a man can/may be mekadesh in the following ways, i.e. himself or with his emissary. So now we see the purpose of the Mishnah is to convey the surprising idea that the initial stage of marriage can be done remotely by a designated third-party.\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִשָּׁה מִתְקַדֶּשֶׁת בָּהּ וּבִשְׁלוּחָהּ","type":"text"}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“The woman is miskadeshes i.e. becomes halachically designated for marriage, via herself or her ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"shaliach","type":"text"}]},{"text":" i.e. emissary, i.e. she may do so.”\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִישׁ מְקַדֵּשׁ אֶת בִּתּוֹ כְּשֶׁהִיא נַעֲרָה בּוֹ וּבִשְׁלוּחוֹ","type":"text"}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“The man is mekadesh his daugher when she is a 12.5 year old girl, via himself or his emissary. Again, we see that the ongoing verb in the Mishnah indicates permissibly, so this should be rendered \"a man ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"may","type":"text"}]},{"text":" initiate the first ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"kiddushin","type":"text"}]},{"text":" step of marriage when his daughter is 12.5, via himself or via his ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"shaliach","type":"text"}]},{"text":" i.e. emissary.”\n","type":"text"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":null,"rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Literal","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Literal","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Literal","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Basic"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Analysis","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Analysis","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Analysis","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Basic"}]}]}],"Analysis":[{"text":"This is a recap of the text of the Mishnah, paying greater attention to nuances and difficulties beyond the simple translation.","type":"text"},{"type":"tool_tip","tokens":[{"text":"Use this step to practice explaining the nuances and difficulties of the text before seeing how the later commentators do so.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִישׁ מְקַדֵּשׁ בּוֹ וּבִשְׁלוּחוֹ\n","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"ha’ish mekadesh bo ub’shlucho","type":"text"}]}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“A man may produce the ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"kiddushin","type":"text"}]},{"text":" stage proceeding marriage with a woman, via himself or via his shaliach i.e. emissary.”\nWe might ask, why did the Mishnah feel it necessary to mention that he can produce ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"kiddushin","type":"text"}]},{"text":" with a woman via himself? Isn’t it be obvious from that there is such a thing as ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"kiddushin","type":"text"}]},{"text":" that the man himself can produce it, otherwise how else would it occur normally?\nAdditionally, perhaps the verses in the Torah which describe the marriage process imply he can do it himself?\nPerhaps the Mishnah has to list every possibility even if the reader already knows one or can infer it from the others? If so, the Mishnah would make more sense. If not, for what purpose might the Mishnah add extra things to a list? Let’s keep the question in mind going forward.\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִשָּׁה מִתְקַדֶּשֶׁת בָּהּ וּבִשְׁלוּחָהּ\n","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"ha’isha miskadeshes bah ub’shluchah","type":"text"}]}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“A woman may become halachically engaged i.e. may accept the ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"kiddushin","type":"text"}]},{"text":" stage of marriage, via herself or via her shaliach i.e. emissary.”\nAgain we might ask why it needs to mention that she can do it herself, as this seems like the standard way it would be done, and even if I didn’t know that initially, telling me she can do it via emissary would seem to imply she can do it herself.\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"text":"הָאִישׁ מְקַדֵּשׁ אֶת בִּתּוֹ כְּשֶׁהִיא נַעֲרָה בּוֹ וּבִשְׁלוּחוֹ\n","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"ha’ish mekadesh es bito k’sh’hi na’arah bo ub’shlucho","type":"text"}]}],"direction":"rtl"},{"text":"“A man can produce the ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"kiddushin","type":"text"}]},{"text":" stage of marriage for his 12.5 year old daughter, via himself or via his shaliach.”\nWe might ask, what is special about a 12.5 year old daughter? What would the ruling be for a 12 year old, or a 13 year old?\nWe can ask again, why do I need to be told he can do it himself? Here it might be less of a problem because this halacha that he can marry off his daughter is perhaps more surprising than the fact that he can marry via himself, and so maybe I do need a Mishnah to tell me both halachos.\nHowever, even if I wouldn’t know before this Mishnah that a man can initiate the marriage process for off his 12.5 year old daughter, once you tell me he can do it with his shaliach i.e. emissary, do I have to be told that he can do it himself, or is that obvious? Again, is it typical of a Mishnah to list redundant things that can be inferred from one another, or is it surprising that it is doing so?\n","type":"text"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":null,"rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Basic","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Basic","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Basic","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Analysis"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Commentary","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Commentary","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Commentary","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Analysis"}]}]}],"Commentary":[{"text":"These are commentators on our Mishnah as it appears in the Gemara.\n","type":"text"},{"topLevelNodes":[{"ordinal":"-","ordered":false,"tokensOfLine":[{"text":"See commentary of ","type":"text"},{"text":"Rashi","type":"disabled_reference","tokens":[{"text":"Rashi","type":"text"}]}],"children":[]},{"ordinal":"-","ordered":false,"tokensOfLine":[{"text":"See commentary of ","type":"text"},{"text":"Gemara","type":"disabled_reference","tokens":[{"text":"Gemara","type":"text"}]}],"children":[]},{"ordinal":"-","ordered":false,"tokensOfLine":[{"text":"See commentary of ","type":"text"},{"text":"Tosofos","type":"disabled_reference","tokens":[{"text":"Tosofos","type":"text"}]}],"children":[]}],"type":"outline"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":null,"rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Analysis","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Analysis","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Analysis","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Commentary"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Summary","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Summary","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Summary","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Commentary"}]}]}],"Summary":[{"text":"This is a summary of our analysis of the Mishnah, not including the conclusions of later Gemaras.","type":"text"},{"type":"tool_tip","tokens":[{"text":"Use this to review our final understanding of the text following all previous steps of analysis.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"block_quote","tokens":[{"type":"bold","tokens":[{"text":"האיש","type":"text"}]},{"text":" מקדש בו ובשלוחו\nהאשה מתקדשת בה ובשלוחה\nהאיש מקדש את בתו כשהיא נערה בו ובשלוחו:","type":"text"}],"direction":"rtl"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":null,"rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Commentary","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Commentary","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Mishnah_Ha’ish_Mekadesh#Commentary","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Summary"}]},{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Gemara","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Gemara","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Kiddushin_41a/Hashta_B’shlucho_Mekadesh","enclosingTopic":"Mishnah Ha’ish Mekadesh","enclosingSubtopic":"Summary"}]}]}]}}